  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: A Harsh Coat That Works Hard for You" imageAlt="Westie puppy being brushed through its white double coat" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Westie's harsh outer coat is functional gear: it repels dirt surprisingly well, sheds very little, and keeps the dog looking respectable on a modest routine. Plan on brushing 2 to 3 times a week, and a groom every 4 to 6 weeks; pet Westies here are clipped rather than hand-stripped, which softens the coat over time but suits our climate and budgets fine.</p>
      <p>Keep baths modest and the shampoo gentle: over-washing dries the skin, and this is the one breed where skin comes before coat in every grooming decision. Ears, nails and daily teeth round out the routine, all with tools from your starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Westie Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Westie puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Westie goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The main conversation for this breed is skin: Westies are prone to atopic dermatitis, itchy, allergic skin that our humidity can aggravate. Not every Westie gets it, but every owner should watch for the early signs, paw licking, ear rubbing, pink or darkened skin, because early vet care keeps it a minor nuisance rather than a chronic misery. Gentle shampoo, thorough drying after wet walks, and flea prevention are the daily defences.</p>
      <p>Beyond skin, the list is standard small-breed fare: patellar luxation and, in some lines, Legg-Calvé-Perthes hip condition. Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. See the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Westie's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Westie puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Westie explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and short, gentle play. The Westie's confidence means it usually settles faster than most; don't mistake the composure for not needing the routine.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks and the terrier opinions arrive. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; early consistency is everything with an independent breed. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

